;; ch07-platformers-jump.book.slatl
;; Book of Arcade Games — Chapter 7: The Platformer's Jump

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Arcade Games"
  :chapter-number      7
  :title               "The Platformer's Jump"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "arcade-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + game-design"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :draws-from-preserved (:book "book-of-games-preserved" :ch 12)
  :prose
"The jump is the hardest simple thing in game design.

You press a button. A character leaves the ground, arcs through the air,
lands. That is one physics equation and two frames of state (grounded,
airborne). And yet: a jump can feel wrong in a hundred different ways.
Too heavy. Too floaty. Too twitchy. Insufficient hangtime at the apex.
Missing coyote time. Missing input buffer. Landing thud not matched to
fall distance. Camera judder on landing. The very best platformers spend
YEARS tuning the jump. Everything else in the game arranges itself
around the character's ability to arc between two platforms and land
where the player expected.

This chapter tunes the jump. We start with the raw physics —
`world/gravity!` + `entity/set-vel!` on 'a' press — and add polish
layer by layer until the jump feels great. Variable jump height by
releasing 'a' early. Slow-float apex via `entity/gravity-scale!`.
Coyote time. Jump buffer. Landing-shake sized to fall speed.

By the end you have a jump you would ship. And you have a template you
can drop into any character game.

---

## 7.1 The naive jump

Press 'a'. Set y-velocity to negative. Done.

```scheme
;; Naive jump: y-velocity to -12 on press. Gravity does the rest.
(define (naive-jump)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.6)
  (world/floor! 220)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 200)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 12 16)
    (entity/bounce! p 0)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -12))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 12 16)))))

(big-bang naive-jump)
```

Play it. The player leaps, arcs, lands. It works. It feels lifeless.

Two problems: every jump goes to the exact same height (you cannot
tap-a for a small hop or hold-a for a big leap), and there is no
generosity — if you press 'a' one frame after walking off a ledge,
tough luck.

We will fix both.

---

## 7.2 Variable jump height

Hold 'a' longer for a higher jump. Release early to cut short.

```scheme
;; Variable jump: release 'a' early cuts the ascent.
(define (variable-jump)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.6)
  (world/floor! 220)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 200)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 12 16)
    (entity/bounce! p 0)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -12))
       ;; If ascending AND 'a' not held: cut ascent (fall faster).
       (when (and (not (input/down? 'a))
                  (< (cadr (entity/vel p)) 0))
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p))
                          (* (cadr (entity/vel p)) 0.5)))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 12 16)))))

(big-bang variable-jump)
```

The block after the jump-press is the whole trick. Every frame we
check: is the player rising (vy < 0), AND is 'a' NOT held? If yes,
halve vy. This effectively terminates the ascent whenever the button
releases.

Tap 'a' quickly: small hop, maybe 15 pixels. Hold 'a' through the
whole ascent: full 60-pixel leap. The single button now has infinite
variability.

Every platformer worth playing has this. Kids feel the difference
within three presses.

---

## 7.3 Apex hang

Gravity should be lower at the top of the arc so the player hangs.
Increase gravity on descent.

```scheme
;; Apex hang: gravity-scale is 0.6 when rising, 1.0 when falling.
(define (hang-jump)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.6)
  (world/floor! 220)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 200)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 12 16)
    (entity/bounce! p 0)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -12))
       (when (and (not (input/down? 'a))
                  (< (cadr (entity/vel p)) 0))
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p))
                          (* (cadr (entity/vel p)) 0.5)))
       ;; Apex-hang: dial gravity-scale based on vy.
       (cond
         ((< (cadr (entity/vel p)) -3)
          (entity/gravity-scale! p 0.7))    ;; rising fast — normal
         ((< (cadr (entity/vel p)) 1)
          (entity/gravity-scale! p 0.4))    ;; near apex — float
         (else
          (entity/gravity-scale! p 1.2)))   ;; falling — heavier
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 12 16)))))

(big-bang hang-jump)
```

`entity/gravity-scale! p k` multiplies world gravity for this entity
only. At 0.7 the player is a little floaty; at 0.4 near the apex, they
seem to pause; at 1.2 on descent, they slam back down.

That combination — float up, hang at top, fall fast — is what
distinguishes a good platformer jump from a physical one. Real gravity
is symmetric; game gravity is asymmetric.

---

## 7.4 Coyote time

If the player runs off a ledge, they get a few frames of grace to
still jump. The character 'coyote's — pauses in the air just long
enough to save the button-press. Named after the cartoon that DIDN'T
have this feature.

```scheme
;; Coyote time: 6 frames of jump-grace after leaving the ground.
(define grounded? #t)
(define coyote-frames 0)

(define (coyote-jump)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.6)
  (world/floor! 220)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 200)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 12 16)
    (entity/bounce! p 0)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       ;; Ground check: are we near the floor?
       (let ((now-grounded? (>= (entity/y p) 212)))
         (when (and grounded? (not now-grounded?))
           ;; Just left the ground — start coyote timer.
           (set! coyote-frames 6))
         (set! grounded? now-grounded?))
       (when (> coyote-frames 0)
         (set! coyote-frames (- coyote-frames 1)))
       ;; Jump if grounded OR within coyote window.
       (when (and (input/pressed? 'a)
                  (or grounded? (> coyote-frames 0)))
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -12)
         (set! coyote-frames 0))
       (when (and (not (input/down? 'a))
                  (< (cadr (entity/vel p)) 0))
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p))
                          (* (cadr (entity/vel p)) 0.5)))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 12 16)
       (paint-text (if grounded? \"grounded\" \"AIRBORNE\") 10 10)
       (paint-text (string-append \"coyote: \" (number->string coyote-frames))
                   10 20)))))

(big-bang coyote-jump)
```

The kid runs to the edge of the floor, off the edge, and taps 'a'
mid-air. If they are within six frames of leaving, the jump fires.
That is 0.1 seconds — invisible to conscious perception, but the
kid's SUBCONSCIOUS notices, and the game feels 'fair.'

Without coyote time, edges feel punishing. With it, edges feel
generous. Both are the same edge.

---

## 7.5 Jump buffer

If the player presses 'a' shortly BEFORE landing, buffer the press so
it fires on landing.

```scheme
;; Jump buffer: 'a' pressed within 8 frames before landing = fire on
;; land.
(define buffered-jump-frames 0)

(define (buffered-jump)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.6)
  (world/floor! 220)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 200)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 12 16)
    (entity/bounce! p 0)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       (let ((now-grounded? (>= (entity/y p) 212)))
         (when (input/pressed? 'a)
           (if now-grounded?
               (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -12)
               (set! buffered-jump-frames 8)))
         ;; If buffered and we JUST landed: fire the buffered jump.
         (when (and now-grounded? (> buffered-jump-frames 0))
           (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -12)
           (set! buffered-jump-frames 0)))
       (when (> buffered-jump-frames 0)
         (set! buffered-jump-frames (- buffered-jump-frames 1)))
       (when (and (not (input/down? 'a))
                  (< (cadr (entity/vel p)) 0))
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p))
                          (* (cadr (entity/vel p)) 0.5)))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 12 16)))))

(big-bang buffered-jump)
```

Kids running off a ledge and pressing 'a' juuust before landing feel
respected. The game listens even when they are 'wrong' by strict
timing.

---

## 7.6 Landing shake

Big drops deserve a bigger thud.

```scheme
;; Landing shake sized to fall velocity.
(define was-airborne? #f)

(define (thumpy-jump)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.6)
  (world/floor! 220)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 100)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 12 16)
    (entity/bounce! p 0)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -12))
       (let ((vy (cadr (entity/vel p)))
             (now-grounded? (>= (entity/y p) 212)))
         ;; Just landed?
         (when (and was-airborne? now-grounded?)
           (world/camera-shake! (max 2 (* vy 0.3)) 0.9))
         (set! was-airborne? (not now-grounded?)))
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 12 16)))))

(big-bang thumpy-jump)
```

A small hop lands with barely a shake. A 100-pixel drop shakes the
whole screen. The player intuits WEIGHT from the feedback.

---

## 7.7 Putting it together — the good jump

All the tricks in one player controller.

```scheme
;; The full-featured jump: variable, apex-hang, coyote, buffer, thump.
(define grounded? #t)
(define was-grounded? #t)
(define coyote-frames 0)
(define buffered-jump 0)

(define (great-jump)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.6)
  (world/floor! 220)
  (let ((p (world/spawn 'player 160 200)))
    (entity/shape! p 'rect 12 16)
    (entity/bounce! p 0)
    (entity/solid! p #t)
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (when (input/down? 'left)  (entity/move! p -3 0))
       (when (input/down? 'right) (entity/move! p 3 0))
       (set! grounded? (>= (entity/y p) 212))
       ;; Coyote update.
       (when (and was-grounded? (not grounded?))
         (set! coyote-frames 6))
       (when (> coyote-frames 0)
         (set! coyote-frames (- coyote-frames 1)))
       ;; Jump-press: fire if grounded/coyote, else buffer.
       (when (input/pressed? 'a)
         (if (or grounded? (> coyote-frames 0))
             (begin
               (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -12)
               (set! coyote-frames 0))
             (set! buffered-jump 8)))
       ;; Buffered jump fires on land.
       (when (and grounded? (> buffered-jump 0))
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p)) -12)
         (set! buffered-jump 0))
       (when (> buffered-jump 0)
         (set! buffered-jump (- buffered-jump 1)))
       ;; Variable jump height.
       (when (and (not (input/down? 'a))
                  (< (cadr (entity/vel p)) 0))
         (entity/set-vel! p (car (entity/vel p))
                          (* (cadr (entity/vel p)) 0.5)))
       ;; Apex hang via gravity-scale.
       (cond
         ((< (cadr (entity/vel p)) -3) (entity/gravity-scale! p 0.7))
         ((< (cadr (entity/vel p)) 1)  (entity/gravity-scale! p 0.4))
         (else                          (entity/gravity-scale! p 1.2)))
       ;; Landing thump.
       (when (and (not was-grounded?) grounded?)
         (world/camera-shake!
          (max 2 (* (cadr (entity/vel p)) 0.3)) 0.9))
       (set! was-grounded? grounded?)
       (world/step)
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'player (entity/x p) (entity/y p) 12 16)))))

(big-bang great-jump)
```

Play this. If you have played any of the classic platformers, you will
recognize the feel: forgiving, expressive, thumpy. About 40 lines
between the raw jump and this one, and every line is one of the eight
knobs from chapter 6.

---

## 7.8 The four patterns in a platformer

**Composition.** The player controller is a stack of small compositions:
gravity, gravity-scale, jump-press-handler, coyote-timer, jump-buffer,
land-shake. Each is a small stateful cell (`grounded?`, `coyote-frames`,
`buffered-jump`, `was-grounded?`) mutated per frame.

**Orchestration.** Order-of-updates matters and is subtle. Update
`grounded?` after physics settles, so the check is accurate. Fire
buffered jump BEFORE variable-height cut, so the cut doesn't
immediately nerf the buffered leap. Landing-shake needs to compare
this frame's grounded to LAST frame's grounded — hence
`was-grounded?`.

**In-routing.** The 'a' button routes to different handlers depending
on state: if grounded, fire jump; if airborne and ascending, cut jump
short (on release); if airborne and 'a' pressed, buffer. One button,
three routes.

**Routing.** Landing routes to camera-shake. Variable-height routes
to velocity. Coyote-timer routes back to input-eligibility. Every
frame is a small router table.

---

## 7.9 Common desktop tasks

**Fetch-decision toy.** A shop with lots of scrollable items presents
a small jump-to-collect: the customer's cursor is a character running
along a row of items; a tap makes them jump to grab an item; hold to
reach higher shelves. The jump curve determines what they can reach.
Playful shopping.

**Timing-check onboarding.** A shop welcoming new users runs a
30-second platformer tutorial as its splash — 'jump across three gaps
to enter.' Kids get in fast. The abandon-rate on 3-gap tutorials is
lower than on 3-tap tutorials, because doing feels better than
watching.

---

## 7.10 Pitfalls

**Player falls through the floor at high fall speed.** Tunneling. The
one-frame delta at terminal velocity exceeds the floor thickness.
Cap fall speed with `entity/max-speed!` or use `entity/gravity-scale!
p 0.5` at high vy to cap gently.

**Jump feels too floaty.** Reduce max jump velocity from -12 to -10,
increase gravity from 0.6 to 0.8. Also check that gravity-scale
returns to 1.2 (or higher) on descent.

**Coyote fires from ceilings.** Your `grounded?` check compares to
floor y=220, but the player may touch a ceiling and register grounded
briefly. Distinguish floor-contact from any-contact via layer-based
collision.

**Buffered jump fires on death.** Clear `buffered-jump` on death or
respawn.

**Apex hang looks weird when player is falling from a standstill.**
The gravity-scale conditional keys off velocity, not intent. If the
player was falling from a jump vs stepping off a platform, the
gravity-scale is the same. Usually fine, but for finicky feel you can
gate hang to 'only after a jump.'

---

## 7.11 Try this yourself

1. Tune max jump velocity from -12 to -8, -14, -20. Find the value
   that feels HEROIC without breaking the game.
2. Add double-jump: on the second press mid-air, if not-yet-double-
   jumped, fire another jump at -9 (weaker second jump).
3. Wall-jump: on collision with a wall while airborne, spring off
   at (5 * heading-x, -8).
4. Dash: 'b' button, sets vx to +/-8 for 6 frames while ignoring
   gravity. Chapter 6's ease applies.
5. Trampoline block: an entity with `entity/bounce! 1.5` that the
   player lands on and gets launched 20% higher.
6. Ledge grab: on collision with the corner of a platform while
   airborne, hold player at that y with `entity/pin!` until 'a' is
   pressed for a mantle-up.

---

## 7.12 What we built

A jump. Variable height. Apex hang. Coyote time. Jump buffer. Landing
shake. The full-featured platformer controller in about 40 lines of
per-frame logic. Every gaming platformer from the last 20 years uses
some subset of these tricks; the great ones use all of them.

Next chapter: leave the fixed screen behind. Build a tile world large
enough that the camera must scroll. Grids, tile-based collision,
level design as data.")

